Are we clear?

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:46.670
ERIC SCHMIDT: That's
very, very clear.

00:06:46.670 --> 00:06:48.000
STEPHEN COLBERT: It does, the
Second Amendment guarantees

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:49.922
all other liberties.

00:06:49.922 --> 00:06:53.260
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHING]

00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:54.710
AUDIENCE: Why did comedy,
kind of, become your

00:06:54.710 --> 00:06:55.810
thing, do you think?

00:06:55.810 --> 00:06:58.760
Or did comedy kind
of pick you?

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:00.380
STEPHEN COLBERT: Well, that's
a nice way of putting it.

00:07:00.380 --> 00:07:01.550
That's a nice way
of putting it.

00:07:01.550 --> 00:07:10.695
I would say, I can't under
emphasize how important comedy

00:07:10.695 --> 00:07:12.740
has been to my life.

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:15.685
And how important certain
opportunities that came along

00:07:15.685 --> 00:07:18.520
to my life, and many of them
seem sort of accidental.

00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:20.040
I went to college
to be an actor.

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:20.980
But an actor, actor.

00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:23.830
I wore black and
I had a beard.

00:07:23.830 --> 00:07:27.310
I was like, let me share my
misery with you, you know.

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:30.150
And then I accidentally met some
people from Second City

00:07:30.150 --> 00:07:32.540
and took some classes there and
got invited to audition.

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:36.110
And accidentally, just sort of a
happy accident, fell in with

00:07:36.110 --> 00:07:37.460
some great people.

00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:40.730
And I quit Second
City four times.

00:07:40.730 --> 00:07:42.440
I kept on returning
to doing comedy.

00:07:42.440 --> 00:07:44.090
And I was backstage one night.

00:07:44.090 --> 00:07:46.170
And this is really the thing
that made the decision for me.

00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:49.550
Somebody was on stage, and they
were supposed to do a

00:07:49.550 --> 00:07:50.790
very simple blackout.

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:52.830
A blackout is a very short--
it's got one joke, and then

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:53.610
the lights go out.

00:07:53.610 --> 00:07:54.740
This is Second City.

00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:56.350
It's a pace keeper
for the show.

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:59.370
She goes out there and the
blackout is this, she goes--

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:01.750
you're supposed to say, I'd like
to do a song for you now.

00:08:01.750 --> 00:08:04.240
Welcome to the No Exit Cafe.

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:05.870
I'd like to do a song
for you right now.

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:07.850
A song for the whales.

00:08:07.850 --> 00:08:11.600
And then you tune up your
guitar for a long time.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:13.440
This is a song for the whales.

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:14.958
And then you go--

00:08:14.958 --> 00:08:16.874
[IMITATING WHALES]

00:08:16.874 --> 00:08:18.790
[CLICKING]

00:08:18.790 --> 00:08:19.690
STEPHEN COLBERT: It's
very simple.

00:08:19.690 --> 00:08:21.610
You do whistle and clicks
and everything.

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:23.140
It's fine.

00:08:23.140 --> 00:08:23.880
Not a great laugh.

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.800
But it works every time.

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:27.680
She goes out there to do it.

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:29.610
I'd like to do a song
for you right now.

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:31.540
I'd like to do a song
for you right now.

00:08:31.540 --> 00:08:33.280
She just goes into her whistling
and her clicking.

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:35.480
And we're backstage waiting
to go on for the next

00:08:35.480 --> 00:08:36.830
scene, me and Dave.

00:08:36.830 --> 00:08:40.130
And we said, it's not
getting any laughs.

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:41.820
This is fool proof.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:42.720
No laughs at all.

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:43.320
What's going on?

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:44.540
Something's wrong.

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:47.815
And then she goes, oh, I forgot
it's song for whales.

00:08:54.530 --> 00:08:58.530
And we burst into laughter
backstage.

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:01.780
And we threw our arms around
each other in the

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:05.930
agony of her failure.

00:09:05.930 --> 00:09:10.880
And just laughing, we fell
like a collapsing teepee.

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:12.830
We just fell to the ground.

00:09:12.830 --> 00:09:16.460
And Dave's feet went out
onto stage, like this.

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:20.000
As we held each other
like lovers.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.560
The most intimate, joyful
experience at her pain, that

00:09:23.560 --> 00:09:24.520
we all knew.

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:26.850
And she could hear it happen,
and the audience

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:27.600
could see our feet.

00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:31.020
And she started laughing
at how wonderfully

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:33.300
she had just failed.

00:09:33.300 --> 00:09:36.590
And I thought at that moment,
this is what I want.

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:42.930
If failure of this scale can
cause this much joy for any

00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:45.730
one, then this is the healthiest
thing that I could

00:09:45.730 --> 00:09:46.950
do with the rest of my life.

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:49.060
And I will do nothing else.

00:09:49.060 --> 00:09:51.160
And I've never looked back
from that moment.

00:09:51.160 --> 00:09:55.960
[APPLAUSE]

00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:57.460
ERIC SCHMIDT: Stephen Colbert,
